il everyone was on the station... but what then?  Would the shuttle fleet still be grounded?  You have 10 astronauts on the station and one Soyuz that can seat 3.  So let's assume 3 leave for Earth immediately to reduce the drain on the station's provisions of air, water, food etc.  That leaves 7 astronauts with no means to return to Earth.  Russia only has one or two Soyuz in 'stock'... I guess you would have to take the risk and send another shuttle with 2 people aboard, docking hardware for the ISS, and attempt a rescue... now, what do you do with the dead Columbia in orbit?  It's fuel supplies exhausted, would you place it in a parked orbit and try to salvage it at a later date?  Would someone need to fly it back down and risk their life, or could it be done 100% automated as the Russian Buran shuttle was?  So many 'What if's'... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 140<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/3/03 10:23 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=820.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear power in space could have saved Columbia&gt;</span><hr size=1> The shuttle, like every other high tech device, comes with its very own self-destruct system.  My guess would be if it cannot be salvaged, it would be driven into the ocean and exploded. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cotopaxi@nuclearspace>cotopaxi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/3/03 11:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=820.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear power in space could have saved Columbia&gt;</span><hr size=1> Nope, shuttle can be used if only to test rescue modifications for the future.<br>
<br>
Re-entry during high level ionosphere and subsequent lower atmospheres from the 70-15 mile altitude range should require a crew ejection &quot;rescue module&quot; that can be detachable from the main fuselage preferably this would be the crew cockpit area of the shuttle.<br>
<br>
In this design the nose end of fuselage would break off from the main fuselage by explosive attachments to essentially &quot;blow&quot; forward and off center from the line of flight. The &quot;rescue module&quot; which would be made of ablative heat resistant material would parachute safely to the ground/water upon re-entry decent.<br>
<br>
Sounds simple and the idea has been suggested before. But as usual critics have always whined…&quot;Why, have this add-on feature when in effect it would never be used and costs too much to implement.&quot;<br>
Personally, any winged spacecraft attempting to enter any atmosphere should have this rescue option built in and available. If a similar idea can work to save military fighter pilots why couldn't it work for an astronaut crew (eject) &quot;rescue module&quot; ?<br>
<br>
